E. COLI EHEC - USA (38): (CALIFORNIA)
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 11 Dec 2017 9:05 PM PDT
Source: KFSN-TV Fresno, ABC News [edited]
http://abc30.com/health/2-valley-children-are-fighting-to-recover-from-e-coli/2770943/


The 13 and 9 year old sisters [from Clovis, Fresno county] were active and healthy kids with no medical history. Their parents thought it was a terrible case of the flu. Originally their pediatrician thought it was the norovirus. But after days of worsening symptoms, they were admitted to Valley Children's Hospital [in Madera county] with _E. coli_.

The 13-year-old is finally starting to improve after 16 days in the hospital. She's had more blood transfusions than she can count along with excruciating stomach pain and she was hallucinating. The sisters were diagnosed with _E. coli_ HUS [hemolytic uremic syndrome] but the girls had "unique" cases. Dr Molly Dorfman said, "Their cases were pretty atypical. Particularly the younger sister's case was very, very severe."

This form of bacteria usually originate from contaminated food products. Pinpointing the exact source has been difficult. They haven't traveled anywhere recently. The family hadn't eaten out lately. It is likely other family members also ate what the girls did but did not become violently ill. Even more puzzling, the girls rarely eat the same things. "Which is why we can't figure out what it would have been. The sisters have very different tastes in food, there aren't a lot of foods that they like in common, so it narrows things down quite a bit more."

The younger sister's kidneys still are not working. She has been debilitated by toxins from the infection, and at one point couldn't wake up. Both sisters have had blood transfusion and dialysis.

[Byline: Sontaya Rose]

