ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[These organisms are currently the most common cause of acute renal function in children in the USA related to the Shiga toxin-related hemolytic uremic syndrome. In most cases, even if hemodialysis is required, the kidney injury resolves, but some cases can result in permanent kidney failure and the need for long term hemodialysis. Most of the mortality related to HUS occurs when central nervous systems intervene such as seizures, altered mental status, and ischemic events.

It appears that both sisters became ill in the same timeframe so sister-to-sister transmission cannot be used to explain to question of a common food vehicle. No information is given regarding potentially non-food related transmission such as visiting a petting zoo.

Direct contact with the animals is not required to be infected as the environment around the livestock can be the vehicle for transmission. Indeed, cases of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ (EHEC) illness have occurred linked to buildings a week or more after a petting zoo had been in them, with the outbreak strain still found in the environment 42 weeks after the event, underscoring the need for adequate decontamination of such sites (Varma JK, Greene KD, Reller ME, et al. An outbreak of _E. coli_ O157 following exposure to a contaminated building. JAMA 2003; 290(20): 2709-12; available at http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=197687). - Mod.LL

